In .NET MAUI 10, Android runs in **edge-to-edge mode** by default, which means `adjustResize` no longer shrinks your window — the keyboard overlaps your content instead.

Here are your options:

## Option 1: Use MAUI's built-in `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll`

MAUI automatically scrolls focused inputs into view. If you've disabled it, re-enable it:

```csharp
// In MauiProgram.cs or on your page
Microsoft.Maui.Platform.KeyboardAutoManagerScroll.Connect(handler);
```

Make sure your `Entry`/`Editor` is inside a `ScrollView` or a layout that can resize.

## Option 2: React to keyboard insets manually (Android)

In your `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`:

```csharp
using Android.Views;
using AndroidX.Core.View;

protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)
{
    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);

    ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(Window!.DecorView, new InsetsListener());
}

class InsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
{
    public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
    {
        var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
        // imeInsets.Bottom gives you the keyboard height in px
        v.SetPadding(0, 0, 0, imeInsets.Bottom);
        return insets;
    }
}
```

## Option 3: Keep `adjustResize` and disable edge-to-edge

In `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`:

```csharp
protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)
{
    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);
    // Opt out of edge-to-edge to restore .NET 9 behavior
    Window!.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(true);
}
```

And in `AndroidManifest.xml`, keep:
```xml
<activity android:windowSoftInputMode="adjustResize" ... />
```

---

**Recommendation:** Option 2 is the forward-compatible approach. Option 3 is the quickest fix if you just want .NET 9 behavior back.
